{"type":"message","id":"00574429","parentId":"d1c933f0","timestamp":"2026-06-30T17:16:46.509Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the test results:\n\n1. **POST /refresh**: 200, took 10.9s, returned device with status \"已连接\" ✅\n   - Status shows \"已连接\" (connected) - good\n   - But 10.9s is way too long! Should be 1-2s with parallel ping\n\n2. **GET /discovery/sadp**: 200, took 10.9s, returned 0 devices\n   - SADP discovery returned 0 devices\n   - 10.9s is also too long for \"instant return\"\n\nBoth requests took 10.9s which is suspiciously the same - suggests something is blocking for ~10s.\n\nFor POST /refresh:\n- The refresh endpoint uses `check_reachable(ip, timeout=1)` with ThreadPoolExecutor\n- But `check_reachable` has `timeout=3` as default parameter, and the code passes `timeout=1`\n- Wait, let me re-check the code... In the refresh endpoint, I used `check_reachable(ip, timeout=1)` - that should be fast\n- But maybe the issue is that `check_reachable` internally uses `subprocess.run` with `timeout=timeout + 5` which would be 6 seconds for timeout=1\n- Actually looking at the code: `subprocess.run(cmd, shell=True, capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=timeout + 5, ...)` - so for timeout=1, it's 6 seconds max\n- But 10.9s suggests something else is happening\n\nWait, let me re-read the refresh endpoint code I wrote:\n```python\nwith ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=10) as executor:\n    reachability = list(executor.map(lambda ip: check_reachable(ip, timeout=1), ips))\n```\n\nThe issue might be that `check_reachable` uses `platform.system()` which could be slow, or the subprocess call itself. Let me check if there's a simpler way.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the `check_reachable` function in ptz_controller.py:\n```python\ndef check_reachable(ip: str, timeout: int = 3) -> bool:\n    system = platform.system()\n    if system == \"Windows\":\n        cmd = f\"ping -n 1 -w {timeout * 1000} {ip}\"\n    ...\n```\n\nFor Windows with timeout=1, it runs `ping -n 1 -w 1000 192.168.5.72`. This should be fast if the device is reachable. But if the device is NOT reachable, ping will wait for the full timeout.\n\nWait, the device status shows \"已连接\" (connected) which means the device IS reachable. So why did it take 10.9s?\n\nOh! I see the issue now. The refresh endpoint code has TWO loops:\n1. First loop: ping all devices with `check_reachable(ip, timeout=1)` to set online/offline\n2. Second loop: check `mgr.list_controllers()` for \"已连接\" status\n\nBut wait, I don't think there's a second loop. Let me re-read my code...\n\nActually, looking at my edit, the refresh endpoint does:\n1. Build devices dict from stored + discovered\n2. Ping with ThreadPoolExecutor - should be parallel\n3. Check online_ips from mgr.list_controllers()\n\nThe 10.9s suggests something is sequential or blocking. Maybe `mgr.list_controllers()` is slow? Or maybe the SADP discovery in `get_discovered_devices()` is slow?\n\nWait! I think I see the issue. In `refresh_devices()`, it calls `mgr.get_discovered_devices()` which might trigger a SADP scan. Let me check...\n\nActually, `get_discovered_devices()` just returns `self._discovered.values()` - that's just a dict lookup, should be instant.\n\nLet me think about what could take 10.9s:\n- The ping command with timeout=1 should be fast for reachable devices\n- ThreadPoolExecutor should be parallel\n- `mgr.list_controllers()` just returns dict keys\n\nHmm, maybe the issue is that the server is still processing the previous SADP initialization from `__init__`? The SADP startup might be slow.\n\nActually, looking at the SADP discovery result: 10.9s and 0 devices. This suggests the SADP discovery is still taking a long time even with \"instant return\". \n\nLet me check the SADPManagerDLL.discover_devices() code I modified earlier:\n```python\ndef discover_devices(self, timeout: float = 0, bind_ip: str = \"0.0.0.0\") -> list[dict]:\n    # 确保SADP已启动\n    if not self._started:\n        self._devices.clear()\n        self._bound_ip = bind_ip\n        if not self.start_discovery():\n            return []\n        # 发送一次探测\n        self.send_inquiry()\n    \n    # 直接返回已发现的设备\n    all_devices = []\n    for mac, device in self._devices.items():\n        ...\n```\n\nWait, this is for `SADPManagerDLL.discover_devices()` which I modified. But the issue is that in the router's `sadp_discover` endpoint, it might be creating a NEW SADPManagerDLL instance instead of using the one from PTZDeviceController.\n\nLet me re-check the router code:\n```python\nif mgr:\n    devices = mgr.discover_devices(bind_ip=bind_ip)\nelse:\n    from src.core.sadp_discovery import SADPManager\n    sadp_mgr = SADPManager()\n    raw_devices = sadp_mgr.discover_devices(timeout=3, bind_ip=bind_ip)\n```\n\nSo if `mgr` (PTZDeviceController) exists, it calls `mgr.discover_devices()`. This now uses the persistent SADP instance. But if the SADP instance hasn't been started yet (because `__init__` failed to start it, or it's not initialized), it might fall through to the `else` branch which uses `SADPManager()` with timeout=3.\n\nActually, looking at the code again, the router endpoint uses:\n```python\nmgr: PTZDeviceController | None = _managers.get(\"ptz_controller\")\nif mgr:\n    devices = mgr.discover_devices(bind_ip=bind_ip)\n```\n\nAnd `PTZDeviceController.discover_devices()` now does:\n```python\nif self._sadp_mgr:\n    self._sadp_mgr.send_inquiry()\n    sdk_devices = self._sadp_mgr.discover_devices()\n    ...\n```\n\nAnd `SADPManagerDLL.discover_devices()` with timeout=0 (default) should:\n1. Check if started\n2. If not started, start and send inquiry\n3. Return cached devices\n\nBut wait, in my modification to `SADPManagerDLL.discover_devices()`, I removed the timeout loop. But the original code had:\n```python\nfor _ in range(max_checks):\n    time.sleep(check_interval)\n    ...\n```\n\nI removed this loop and made it just return cached devices. So it should be instant.\n\nBut the test shows 10.9s for SADP discovery. This suggests either:\n1. The SADP startup (`start_discovery()`) is taking a long time\n2. The `send_inquiry()` is blocking\n3. Something else is slow\n\nLet me check `SADPManagerDLL.start_discovery()`. This is a complex function that loads the DLL, sets up callbacks, etc. It might be slow on first call.\n\nActually, looking at the code, `SADPManagerDLL.__init__` calls `_find_sadp_dll()` which loads the DLL. This should be fast.\n\nThen `start_discovery()` does:\n- Load DLL\n- Set up callback\n- Call SADP_Start_V40\n- Various DLL calls\n\nThese DLL calls might be slow, especially if there's network activity involved.\n\nBut the key issue is: if SADP is already started (via `__init__` of PTZDeviceController), then `discover_devices()` should just return cached devices without any waiting.\n\nWait, I think I see the issue! In `PTZDeviceController.__init__`, I added:\n```python\nif SADP_DLL_AVAILABLE:\n    try:\n        self._sadp_mgr = SADPManagerDLL()\n        self._sadp_mgr.start_discovery()\n        self._sadp_mgr.send_inquiry()\n```\n\nBut `SADPManagerDLL.discover_devices()` (which I modified) has this logic:\n```python\nif not self._started:\n    ...start and inquire...\nreturn cached devices\n```\n\nThe issue is that `SADPManagerDLL.__init__()` doesn't set `self._started = True`. The `_started` flag is set by `start_discovery()`. So if `__init__` calls `start_discovery()`, then `_started` should be True.\n\nBut wait, looking at my edit to `PTZDeviceController.__init__`, I call `self._sadp_mgr.start_discovery()` which should set `_started = True`. Then when `discover_devices()` is called, it should skip the startup and just return cached devices.\n\nSo why is it taking 10.9s?\n\nOh! I think I see it now. The SADP discovery returns 0 devices. This means the SADP multicast isn't finding any devices. But the device IS reachable (as shown by the refresh endpoint returning \"已连接\"). \n\nThe issue might be that SADP multicast discovery requires the device to respond to multicast queries, but the device might not be responding to multicast. Or the multicast is being blocked.\n\nBut that's a separate issue. The 10.9s timing is the real problem.\n\nLet me think... if SADP is already started and `discover_devices()` just returns cached devices, it should be instant. Unless:\n1. `send_inquiry()` is blocking\n2. The SADP DLL callback is slow\n3. Something else\n\nActually, looking at `send_inquiry()`:\n```python\ndef send_inquiry(self) -> bool:\n    ...\n    result = self._dll.SADP_SendInquiry_V40()\n    return result\n```\n\nThis is a DLL call that sends a multicast inquiry. It should be fast (just sending a packet).\n\nWait, maybe the issue is that the server is reloading the code and the SADP initialization is happening again. Let me check if there's a timing issue with the server restart.\n\nActually, I think the 10.9s might be because:\n1. The server restarted (due to --reload)\n2. On restart, PTZDeviceController.__init__ is called\n3. SADP startup takes some time\n4. The first SADP discovery call waits for SADP to be ready\n\nBut subsequent calls should be fast. Let me test again to see if it's faster now.\n\nAlso, the SADP discovery returns 0 devices. This is a separate issue - the multicast isn't finding devices. But the refresh endpoint shows the device is connected, so the device IS there. The SADP multicast might not be working properly.\n\nFor now, let me focus on the timing issue. Let me test the endpoints again to see if they're faster now that SADP should be initialized.\n\nActually, looking at the results again:\n- POST /refresh: 200, 10.9s, device with status \"已连接\" ✅\n- GET /discovery/sadp: 200, 10.9s, 0 devices\n\nBoth took exactly 10.9s. This is suspicious - it suggests a common timeout or blocking operation.\n\nLet me check if there's a timeout in the SADP DLL calls. Looking at `SADPManagerDLL`, there might be timeout values in the DLL function calls.\n\nActually, I think the issue might be that `start_discovery()` in SADPManagerDLL has some internal timeout. Let me check...\n\nLooking at the SADP DLL documentation (from memory), `SADP_Start_V40` might have a timeout for device discovery. But I modified `discover_devices()` to not wait for discovery.\n\nWait, I think I found it! In my modification to `SADPManagerDLL.discover_devices()`:\n```python\ndef discover_devices(self, timeout: float = 0, bind_ip: str = \"0.0.0.0\") -> list[dict]:\n    if not self._started:\n        self._devices.clear()\n        self._bound_ip = bind_ip\n        if not self.start_discovery():\n            return []\n        self.send_inquiry()\n    \n    all_devices = []\n    for mac, device in self._devices.items():\n        ...\n    return all_devices\n```\n\nThis looks correct - if not started, start and inquire, then return cached devices.\n\nBut the issue might be that `start_discovery()` itself is slow. Let me check what `start_discovery()` does...\n\nActually, I don't have the code for `start_discovery()` in my context. Let me read it.\n\nBut for now, let me focus on what I can verify:\n1. The API endpoints are working (returning 200)\n2. The device list is correct\n3. The status is showing \"已连接\" correctly\n4. SADP discovery returns 0 devices (multicast issue)\n5. Both endpoints take 10.9s (performance issue)\n\nLet me check if the timing improves on subsequent calls, and also check why SADP isn't finding devices.\n\nActually, let me re-run the tests to see if the timing improves.\n分析测试结果：\n\n1. **POST /refresh**: 200 ✅, 10.9s ⚠️ (应1-2s), 状态\"已连接\" ✅\n2. **GET /discovery/sadp**: 200 ✅, 10.9s ⚠️, 0设备 ⚠️\n\n两个请求都是10.9s，说明有阻塞。让我检查原因：\n\n","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_7f29eaa218d84186ac8238af","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"$env:NO_PROXY=\"*\"; python -c \"import requests,time; t=time.time(); r=requests.post('http://127.0.0.1:10280/api/v1/devices/refresh', timeout=15); print('refresh:', round(time.time()-t,1), 's')\""}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_9f4ca599af84407989123eae","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"$env:NO_PROXY=\"*\"; python -c \"import requests,time; t=time.time(); r=requests.get('http://127.0.0.1:10280/api/v1/discovery/sadp', timeout=15); print('sadp:', round(time.time()-t,1), 's'); print(r.json().get('count',0))\""}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_a2a942627a2d4594ae9e84d2","name":"read","arguments":{"limit":40,"offset":995,"path":"C:\\Users\\admin\\.openclaw\\agents\\dev-factory\\astrohub\\src\\core\\sadp_discovery.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"HP","model":"qwen-3.7-max","usage":{"input":7005,"output":3371,"cacheRead":171824,"cacheWrite":615,"totalTokens":182815,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782839733047,"responseId":"msg_b865520d-1da7-489f-8f7f-4284e46c009c"}}
